INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '693c53fe-4d5b-413a-aacd-22309d5a3cf7',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$matplotlib + Pandas groupby — Plot Aggregated DataFrames in One Call$escape$,
  $escape$Pandas DataFrames integrate directly with matplotlib's plotting API via `.plot()`, but the real power shows when you combine `groupby` aggregations with visualization. Instead of manually looping through groups and calling `ax.bar()` repeatedly, pass grouped results straight into matplotlib-aware plot methods.

When you call `df.groupby('category')['value'].mean().plot(kind='bar')`, Pandas delegates to `matplotlib.pyplot` under the hood, setting tick labels from the index and values from the Series. For multi-column aggregations, `df.groupby('region')[['sales','returns']].sum().plot(kind='bar')` produces grouped bars automatically — matplotlib creates one bar cluster per index label.

For finer control, unstack a MultiIndex groupby into columns first: `df.groupby(['year','quarter'])['revenue'].sum().unstack().plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=ax)`. This lets matplotlib's `Axes.bar` handle stacking natively. Always pass an explicit `ax` when embedding in subplots — relying on the implicit `pyplot` state machine leads to figure leaks in loops.$escape$,
  $escape$import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

df = pd.DataFrame({
    'region': ['East','East','West','West','East','West'],
    'quarter': ['Q1','Q2','Q1','Q2','Q1','Q2'],
    'sales': [120, 150, 90, 200, 130, 170]
})

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(10, 4))

df.groupby('region')['sales'].sum().plot(kind='bar', ax=ax1, title='Sales by Region')

df.groupby(['region','quarter'])['sales'].sum().unstack().plot(
    kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=ax2, title='Stacked by Quarter')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()$escape$,
