INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'b2d836ae-4607-4dd1-8ad6-34c1d5611f6a',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$matplotlib Visualization Best Practices — Charts, Color, and Cutting Chartjunk$escape$,
  $escape$Choosing the right chart in matplotlib starts with your data's relationship type. Use `plt.bar()` for categorical comparisons, `plt.plot()` for trends over time, `plt.scatter()` for correlations, and `plt.hist()` for distributions — never substitute one for another just for aesthetics.

For color accessibility, avoid the default `tab10` cycle when distinguishing critical data. Use `plt.cm.viridis` or `plt.cm.cividis` for sequential data — both are perceptually uniform and colorblind-safe. For diverging data, prefer `RdBu` or `coolwarm`. Always validate with `matplotlib.colors.to_rgba()` if programmatically generating palettes.

Chartjunk in matplotlib is death by a thousand defaults: remove redundant spines with `ax.spines[['top', 'right']].set_visible(False)`, eliminate gridlines unless they aid reading via `ax.grid(False)`, and never use `plt.title()` alone — pair it with `ax.set_xlabel()` and `ax.set_ylabel()` for full context. Use `tight_layout()` or `constrained_layout=True` in `plt.subplots()` to prevent label clipping without manual padding hacks.$escape$,
  $escape$import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 5), constrained_layout=True)

x = np.linspace(0, 10, 100)
ax.plot(x, np.sin(x), color='#0072B2')  # colorblind-safe blue

# Remove chartjunk
ax.spines[['top', 'right']].set_visible(False)
ax.grid(False)

ax.set_title('matplotlib — Sine Wave', fontsize=14, pad=12)
ax.set_xlabel('X', fontsize=11)
ax.set_ylabel('sin(X)', fontsize=11)

plt.show()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
